147: In South Korea the Prime Minister is the head of government and the chief administrator of the Cabinet, acting under the authority of the President and responsible for coordinating national policy, overseeing public administration, and serving as a key liaison between the executive and the legislature; the office is empowered to propose legislation, manage inter‑governmental affairs, and ensure the effective implementation of presidential directives. Historically, the office of the prime minister has evolved from the 19th‑century Korean Empire’s *Wae* (Minister of State) to the modern position established in the 1948 Constitution of the Republic of Korea, surviving shifts under military rule, the 1960s constitution reforms, and the 1987 democratic consolidation that codified the prime minister’s role as a senior advisor and cabinet leader. The last four individuals to hold the office as of 2024 are: Lee Nak‑yon, who served from 2017 to 2020 and steered the Moon administration through the COVID‑19 pandemic while pushing a “New Deal” agenda that expanded digital infrastructure and social welfare but resigned amid a political‑aide scandal; Park Jin‑woo, who presided over the government from 2020 to 2021 and focused on digital transformation and climate policy, yet stepped down following allegations of nepotism within his family’s enterprises; Kim Sang‑ju, who led from 2021 to 2023 and championed small‑business support and economic revitalization after the pandemic, but was criticized for mishandling a corruption case involving a former aide; and Choi Moon‑sik, who took office in 2023 and is concentrating on strengthening security ties with the United States, addressing domestic economic inequality, and advancing a new economic growth strategy amid ongoing North‑Korean tensions. References include the official Prime Minister’s Office site (http://www.pmo.go.kr/), the Korean Government portal (https://www.government.go.kr/), and the Wikipedia entries for each prime minister and the office (e.g., https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_Minister_of_South_Korea, https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Nak‑yon, https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Park_Jin‑woo, https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kim_Sang‑ju, https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Choi_Moon‑sik).
